content.explanation:
Imagine a thermometer reading a boiling pot. Water boils at 100°C. If your thermometer says 99.8°C, that's accurate (very close). If it says 115°C, that's not accurate (far from true value).

Accuracy is about being RIGHT. How close you are to the actual answer. {{viz:anim-01}}

Key idea: There's a TRUE value (like 100°C for boiling water). Your measurement either hits it (accurate) or misses it (inaccurate).

Accuracy tells you: 'Did I measure the right value?'

BUT—you need to KNOW the true value to judge accuracy. If you don't know what's correct, you can't know if you're accurate! {{viz:chart-01}}
